1
00:00:50,844 --> 00:00:57,183
It's funny how you wake up each day and never really know if it will be one that will change your life forever.

2
00:00:58,143 --> 00:00:59,853
But that's what this day was.

3
00:00:59,936 --> 00:01:03,982
The day I left the city to spend a week in the house where my mother grew up.

4
00:01:04,607 --> 00:01:06,401
A day I'll never forget.

5
00:01:06,494 --> 00:01:12,501
So many years have passed Almost there.

6
00:01:12,521 --> 00:01:18,528
Feeling all right?

7
00:01:18,830 --> 00:01:20,373
I'm okay.

8
00:01:22,427 --> 00:01:39,403
I left my childhood In a garden green Come in the garden And look at the trees I used to play there when I was a child Oh, Hara.

9
00:01:39,423 --> 00:01:56,399
How many times have I told her?

10
00:01:57,545 --> 00:01:58,387
Wait here.

11
00:01:58,407 --> 00:01:59,249
All right?

12
00:01:59,269 --> 00:02:00,111
I won't be a minute.

13
00:02:00,205 --> 00:02:01,372
Okay.

14
00:02:04,385 --> 00:02:06,451
Hara!

15
00:02:06,471 --> 00:02:08,537
Your car's blocking the driveway again.

16
00:02:09,557 --> 00:02:55,604
So many years have passed The dew is still on the roses I left my childhood In a garden green Shawn?

17
00:02:55,624 --> 00:03:41,671
Where are you?

18
00:03:50,815 --> 00:03:51,899
Shawn?

19
00:03:52,317 --> 00:03:54,360
I'm here, Aunt Jessica.

20
00:03:55,069 --> 00:03:57,030
Come meet Hara!

21
00:04:28,895 --> 00:04:41,783
Supper is done and night has come Let's have tea together near the fireplace Nice try.

22
00:04:45,286 --> 00:04:58,758
My house, my home ls so small, so pretty My mom, my dad We are family Joy everywhere Hey, back off!

23
00:05:01,062 --> 00:05:01,959
Hey!

24
00:05:01,979 --> 00:05:02,876
Go get your own!

25
00:05:23,491 --> 00:05:24,992
Arrietty!

26
00:05:25,076 --> 00:05:26,160
What?

27
00:05:26,703 --> 00:05:28,788
You went outside again, didn't you?

28
00:05:29,924 --> 00:05:31,281
How many times have I...

29
00:05:31,301 --> 00:05:32,658
What happened to your room?

30
00:05:32,750 --> 00:05:34,419
It's my own little garden.

31
00:05:34,627 --> 00:05:38,172
If you ask me it looks more like your own little jungle.

32
00:05:39,590 --> 00:05:41,634
Is that a bay leaf?

33
00:05:45,221 --> 00:05:46,514
Where did you get that?

34
00:05:48,015 --> 00:05:50,184
I wanted to wait and give it to you on your birthday, but...

35
00:05:50,268 --> 00:05:51,894
Happy birthday!

36
00:05:54,939 --> 00:05:58,943
This will last me all year.

37
00:06:00,111 --> 00:06:02,405
But the bay tree is so far away.

38
00:06:02,488 --> 00:06:04,866
If a bean saw you it would...

39
00:06:05,074 --> 00:06:06,200
Beans don't scare me.

40
00:06:06,294 --> 00:06:07,609
The beans should scare you.

41
00:06:07,629 --> 00:06:08,944
That's what worries me.

42
00:06:09,036 --> 00:06:10,955
The world is a dangerous place for a Borrower.

43
00:06:11,622 --> 00:06:13,833
Your Aunt Eggletina wasn't scared either and she...

44
00:06:13,926 --> 00:06:15,325
Was eaten by a toad.

45
00:06:15,345 --> 00:06:16,744
I know, I know.

46
00:06:17,211 --> 00:06:19,589
If you don't like your gift I can put it in my room.

47
00:06:19,964 --> 00:06:21,466
No, no, I should keep it.

48
00:06:22,508 --> 00:06:24,552
I have just the recipe for these.

49
00:06:24,635 --> 00:06:26,429
I'll have your father borrow some sugar.

50
00:06:26,888 --> 00:06:28,765
Oh, you don't have to.

51
00:06:28,931 --> 00:06:31,601
Because tonight I'll borrow some for you.

52
00:06:31,684 --> 00:06:32,977
What?

53
00:06:33,561 --> 00:06:35,480
Don't tell me you forgot!

54
00:06:35,563 --> 00:06:37,690
Tonight's my first borrowing!

55
00:06:37,774 --> 00:06:39,942
Look, Papa's home.

56
00:06:41,704 --> 00:06:42,727
Papa.

57
00:06:42,747 --> 00:06:43,770
Papa, I made it all the way to the bay tree today.

58
00:06:44,989 --> 00:06:46,908
And I used the leaves over my head just like you said.

59
00:06:46,991 --> 00:06:49,452
And I didn't even get seen by the cat.

60
00:06:49,545 --> 00:06:51,548
So, what I'm trying to say, - if there was any doubt...

61
00:06:51,568 --> 00:06:53,571
- There's a new bean in the house.

62
00:06:53,664 --> 00:06:54,791
What?

63
00:06:54,884 --> 00:06:55,726
- I know.

64
00:06:55,746 --> 00:06:56,588
I saw him.

65
00:06:56,608 --> 00:06:57,450
- Arrietty, I told you to be...

66
00:06:57,543 --> 00:06:59,587
Yes, Mama, I was careful and he didn't see me.

67
00:06:59,670 --> 00:07:01,798
And he's much smaller than other beans.

68
00:07:01,881 --> 00:07:04,759
Papa, you just have to let me come borrowing tonight.

69
00:07:06,010 --> 00:07:07,720
We know nothing about this new bean.

70
00:07:07,804 --> 00:07:09,972
But you promised this would be my night.

71
00:07:10,056 --> 00:07:11,140
And I've seen him.

72
00:07:11,224 --> 00:07:13,935
Papa, please, I am telling you, he's just a child.

73
00:07:14,268 --> 00:07:17,188
And the children are more vicious than the grownups.

74
00:07:17,271 --> 00:07:19,357
I'll be fine.

75
00:07:23,110 --> 00:07:25,321
Well, the young beans do go to bed early.

76
00:07:25,530 --> 00:07:27,865
Oh, thank you, Papa!

77
00:07:28,241 --> 00:07:29,700
Pod!

78
00:07:29,794 --> 00:07:31,213
The boy is very sickly and weak.

79
00:07:31,233 --> 00:07:32,652
She'll be fine.

80
00:07:32,745 --> 00:07:33,788
But...

81
00:07:35,967 --> 00:07:37,574
Oh, and don't worry, Mother.

82
00:07:37,594 --> 00:07:39,201
I'll get Papa back safely.

83
00:07:42,213 --> 00:07:44,882
Arrietty will be turning 14 soon.

84
00:07:44,966 --> 00:07:47,593
She'll need to know how to take care of herself out there.

85
00:07:47,677 --> 00:07:49,136
Without our help.

86
00:07:49,220 --> 00:07:53,224
Sometimes I worry that we are the only Borrowers left.

87
00:07:55,059 --> 00:07:56,644
What'll become of us?

88
00:08:11,450 --> 00:08:13,452
Remember what the doctor said, Shawn.

89
00:08:13,546 --> 00:08:14,756
Your heart needs rest.

90
00:08:14,776 --> 00:08:15,986
No excitement.

91
00:08:16,090 --> 00:08:17,447
- Is that clear, Hara?

92
00:08:17,467 --> 00:08:18,824
- Yes, ma'am, I'll see to it.

93
00:08:18,926 --> 00:08:21,325
Whatever you need, Shawn, you ask Hara, - and she'll get it for you, all right?

94
00:08:21,345 --> 00:08:23,744
- Yes, Aunt Jessica.

95
00:08:23,838 --> 00:08:25,506
Make him feel at home, Hara.

96
00:08:25,590 --> 00:08:26,966
Yes, ma'am.

97
00:08:35,308 --> 00:08:38,019
We'll start by keeping the bugs out.

98
00:09:23,356 --> 00:09:26,400
Don't you think you should wear something a little darker and longer?

99
00:09:26,484 --> 00:09:28,694
No, I think this one's perfect.

100
00:09:31,614 --> 00:09:34,575
So, I need you to get me some tissue paper and some sugar.

101
00:09:34,659 --> 00:09:39,288
Oh, and promise, dear husband, you won't let our daughter get eaten or squashed like a bug.

102
00:09:39,382 --> 00:09:40,655
Oh, please God.

103
00:09:40,675 --> 00:09:41,948
Please help them.

104
00:09:44,428 --> 00:09:45,159
Don't worry about me.

105
00:09:45,179 --> 00:09:45,910
Everything's fine.

106
00:09:48,933 --> 00:09:49,663
Okay, bye, Mom.

107
00:09:49,683 --> 00:09:50,413
I love you.

108
00:09:50,518 --> 00:09:51,263
Oh, goodbye.

109
00:09:51,283 --> 00:09:52,028
Love you, too.

110
00:09:52,048 --> 00:09:52,793
Stay close to your father.

111
00:09:52,885 --> 00:10:01,936
I will Do I get one of those?

112
00:10:02,738 --> 00:10:03,532
Nope?

113
00:10:03,552 --> 00:10:04,346
Okay.

114
00:10:25,710 --> 00:10:26,919
Arrietty!

115
00:10:45,563 --> 00:10:46,814
Did you see that?

116
00:10:46,897 --> 00:10:48,232
That's my girl.

117
00:10:54,697 --> 00:10:56,240
Don't look down.

118
00:10:57,491 --> 00:10:59,994
One step at a time.

119
00:11:27,114 --> 00:11:28,137
All right.

120
00:11:28,157 --> 00:11:29,180
You need to hold this for me.

121
00:11:29,273 --> 00:11:30,608
Okay.

122
00:12:02,807 --> 00:12:05,976
Arrietty, make sure you hold on tight.

123
00:12:51,814 --> 00:12:53,023
Arrietty!

124
00:12:53,242 --> 00:12:54,348
- Let's go.

125
00:12:54,368 --> 00:12:55,474
- Right.

126
00:14:15,940 --> 00:14:18,734
It's so big.

127
00:14:19,902 --> 00:14:22,112
Papa, what is this place?

128
00:14:22,655 --> 00:14:25,241
This is where beans store all their food.

129
00:14:25,324 --> 00:14:26,784
The sugar is over there.

130
00:14:31,789 --> 00:14:34,124
When you get down there, wait for me.

131
00:14:49,556 --> 00:14:50,599
Yeah!

132
00:15:20,170 --> 00:15:21,839
Papa, you are great!

133
00:15:59,209 --> 00:16:00,461
Yay!

134
00:16:46,433 --> 00:16:47,435
There.

135
00:16:47,455 --> 00:16:48,457
That wasn't so hard.

136
00:16:48,560 --> 00:16:49,750
- Where to now?

137
00:16:49,770 --> 00:16:50,960
- Tissue paper.

138
00:16:50,980 --> 00:16:52,170
Then home.

139
00:17:08,445 --> 00:17:09,863
Papa, look what I found.

140
00:17:11,448 --> 00:17:13,700
Looks like someone got their first borrowing.

141
00:17:14,118 --> 00:17:16,412
Careful with it, it's sharp.

142
00:17:16,495 --> 00:17:17,621
Okay.

143
00:17:39,601 --> 00:17:41,311
Papa, borrowing is so much fun!

144
00:17:47,025 --> 00:17:48,569
Look down there.

145
00:17:54,168 --> 00:17:55,920
Filthy rats.

146
00:17:55,940 --> 00:17:57,692
You want to stay away from those things.

147
00:17:58,454 --> 00:17:59,538
I'm not afraid.

148
00:18:01,331 --> 00:18:04,209
I will cut them down to size with my sword.

149
00:18:05,294 --> 00:18:08,172
Sometimes it's best not to go looking for danger.

150
00:18:55,260 --> 00:18:56,386
What is this place?

151
00:18:57,012 --> 00:19:00,140
I've heard human beans call it a dollhouse.

152
00:19:01,433 --> 00:19:03,268
Dolls are toys for beans.

153
00:19:03,560 --> 00:19:05,562
And we are not toys.

154
00:19:05,896 --> 00:19:08,023
These things are not for borrowing.

155
00:19:08,273 --> 00:19:10,817
Oh, but it's so perfect for us.

156
00:19:11,735 --> 00:19:15,239
Don't you think Mother would absolutely love that dresser over there?

157
00:19:15,322 --> 00:19:18,158
If anything went missing, they'd know right away.

158
00:19:18,242 --> 00:19:20,452
Borrowers take only what they need.

159
00:21:42,886 --> 00:21:44,763
Don't be afraid, okay?

160
00:22:04,533 --> 00:22:05,617
Hey.

161
00:22:07,045 --> 00:22:08,672
I know it was you in the garden.

162
00:22:08,692 --> 00:22:10,319
I knew I saw you.

163
00:22:17,129 --> 00:22:23,760
My mother used to tell me stories about the little people who lived under the floors.

164
00:22:26,263 --> 00:22:27,764
Was it you?

165
00:22:28,348 --> 00:22:29,599
Was it?

166
00:22:31,518 --> 00:22:32,853
Please don't go.

167
00:23:19,576 --> 00:23:20,578
I'm sorry.

168
00:23:20,598 --> 00:23:21,600
I should have told you.

169
00:23:21,693 --> 00:23:24,029
He might have seen me out in the garden today.

170
00:23:25,447 --> 00:23:27,574
We all make mistakes.

171
00:23:27,991 --> 00:23:30,786
So we'll just have to be extra careful now.

172
00:23:31,453 --> 00:23:33,914
Best not to tell your mother about this.

173
00:23:33,997 --> 00:23:35,832
You know how she worries.

174
00:23:36,500 --> 00:23:37,542
Right.

175
00:23:43,006 --> 00:23:44,758
I'm very proud of you.

176
00:23:44,841 --> 00:23:48,303
A lesser Borrower would've panicked and run away.

177
00:24:02,651 --> 00:24:03,735
Well, we're home.

178
00:24:04,361 --> 00:24:05,862
Safe and sound.

179
00:24:17,541 --> 00:24:18,750
Is everything okay?

180
00:24:19,960 --> 00:24:22,337
Not quite the adventure we'd hoped for.

181
00:24:22,420 --> 00:24:25,423
This old light gave out halfway to the kitchen.

182
00:24:26,550 --> 00:24:27,926
No.

183
00:24:28,927 --> 00:24:31,346
Well, I'm afraid we had to give up on the sugar.

184
00:24:31,731 --> 00:24:33,567
That's okay.

185
00:24:33,587 --> 00:24:35,423
I'm just happy you made it home.

186
00:24:36,184 --> 00:24:37,477
It wasn't a total loss.

187
00:24:37,561 --> 00:24:40,814
Arrietty, why don't you show your mother your first borrowing?

188
00:24:50,073 --> 00:24:51,741
What a beautiful pin.

189
00:24:55,380 --> 00:24:56,069
Okay.

190
00:24:56,089 --> 00:24:56,778
Off to bed.

191
00:25:03,920 --> 00:25:05,589
Night, Mama, Papa.

192
00:25:10,719 --> 00:25:12,846
She looks so worn-out.

193
00:25:13,972 --> 00:25:15,765
Should I make us some tea?

194
00:27:48,803 --> 00:27:50,994
Shawn, come inside.

195
00:27:51,014 --> 00:27:53,205
You'll catch your death of cold.

196
00:28:37,519 --> 00:28:38,854
What did you say?

197
00:28:38,874 --> 00:28:40,209
Why would he do that?

198
00:28:40,303 --> 00:28:42,722
I think he was just being nice.

199
00:28:42,806 --> 00:28:46,351
It's the same cube of sugar I dropped in his room last night.

200
00:28:47,977 --> 00:28:51,981
Pod, what does she mean, she dropped it?

201
00:28:56,704 --> 00:28:57,894
Do not touch it.

202
00:28:57,914 --> 00:28:59,104
Do you understand me?

203
00:29:02,617 --> 00:29:04,160
It's a trap.

204
00:29:04,671 --> 00:29:06,090
I just know it.

205
00:29:06,110 --> 00:29:07,529
They're going to trap us like cockroaches.

206
00:29:07,914 --> 00:29:11,251
Homily, let's try not to get hysterical, okay?

207
00:29:11,584 --> 00:29:14,337
Don't tell me to not get hysterical!

208
00:29:14,420 --> 00:29:16,256
We'll probably have to move now.

209
00:29:17,674 --> 00:29:19,843
Goodbye, old table.

210
00:29:19,926 --> 00:29:22,887
We had so many fun times together.

211
00:29:25,140 --> 00:29:28,101
Let's not say goodbye to anything just yet.

212
00:29:28,184 --> 00:29:30,478
Eat your soup before it gets cold.

213
00:29:32,105 --> 00:29:34,649
I told you that young bean would be trouble!

214
00:29:39,195 --> 00:29:41,197
But no one ever listens to me.

215
00:29:56,296 --> 00:29:58,298
Thank you, Arrietty.

216
00:29:58,381 --> 00:30:01,134
Smart girl, doing this when the sun came out.

217
00:30:02,302 --> 00:30:05,096
Or maybe I have a smart mama who taught me.

218
00:30:08,558 --> 00:30:09,851
You're a good girl.

219
00:30:09,934 --> 00:30:12,604
If you've got this, I think I'll go lie down a bit.

220
00:30:12,687 --> 00:30:13,897
Okay.

221
00:35:10,610 --> 00:35:12,111
Is that you from last night?

222
00:35:15,249 --> 00:35:16,105
No, wait.

223
00:35:16,125 --> 00:35:16,981
Don't go.

224
00:35:19,952 --> 00:35:21,787
I'm sorry if I frightened you.

225
00:35:21,871 --> 00:35:23,080
Please leave us alone.

226
00:35:24,373 --> 00:35:26,167
We don't need your help.

227
00:35:27,043 --> 00:35:29,086
But can I please just talk to you?

228
00:35:30,056 --> 00:35:31,433
No!

229
00:35:31,453 --> 00:35:32,830
Human beans are dangerous.

230
00:35:32,934 --> 00:35:34,394
Whenever we're seen, we have to move.

231
00:35:34,414 --> 00:35:35,874
My parents said so.

232
00:35:37,104 --> 00:35:38,606
So you have a family.

233
00:35:38,626 --> 00:35:40,128
That must be nice.

234
00:35:41,766 --> 00:35:43,267
You don't have a family?

235
00:35:44,143 --> 00:35:45,603
Yeah, I have one.

236
00:35:45,686 --> 00:35:48,314
But they sent me here to get the care and attention I need.

237
00:35:48,397 --> 00:35:51,525
Because they're both very busy with their work.

238
00:35:52,485 --> 00:35:54,195
Sorry to hear that.

239
00:35:57,625 --> 00:35:59,107
Anyway, my name is Shawn.

240
00:35:59,127 --> 00:36:00,609
What's your name?

241
00:36:03,746 --> 00:36:05,414
What do they call you?

242
00:36:07,124 --> 00:36:10,378
Not that it's any of your business, but it's Arrietty.

243
00:36:11,472 --> 00:36:12,974
Arrietty.

244
00:36:12,994 --> 00:36:14,496
Arrietty.

245
00:36:16,133 --> 00:36:17,510
That's a beautiful name.

246
00:36:20,346 --> 00:36:21,847
Maybe we could be friends?

247
00:36:33,567 --> 00:36:35,903
Could you at least come out so I can see you?

248
00:36:35,987 --> 00:36:37,405
I want to make sure I'm not dreaming.

249
00:36:44,120 --> 00:36:46,914
I won't hurt you, I promise.

250
00:37:01,480 --> 00:37:01,981
Help me!

251
00:37:02,001 --> 00:37:02,502
Help me!

252
00:37:35,681 --> 00:37:36,162
Hey!

253
00:37:36,182 --> 00:37:36,663
Hey!

254
00:37:36,683 --> 00:37:37,164
Hey!

255
00:37:38,434 --> 00:37:40,124
What in the world?

256
00:37:40,144 --> 00:37:41,834
A crow!

257
00:37:44,523 --> 00:37:45,226
Oh!

258
00:37:45,246 --> 00:37:45,949
Attack!

259
00:37:45,969 --> 00:37:46,672
OW!

260
00:37:49,352 --> 00:37:51,979
You get out right now!

261
00:38:03,949 --> 00:38:05,534
What got into that bird?

262
00:38:05,618 --> 00:38:08,329
Don't think I've ever seen one behave like that.

263
00:38:08,412 --> 00:38:11,207
Maybe it's nesting season or something.

264
00:38:11,425 --> 00:38:12,990
I don't know.

265
00:38:13,010 --> 00:38:14,575
Looks me to like it was after something.

266
00:38:14,668 --> 00:38:17,380
Oh, look at the holes in the screen.

267
00:38:17,463 --> 00:38:19,882
Which I'll have to replace, of course.

268
00:38:20,559 --> 00:38:21,520
Oh, my goodness.

269
00:38:21,540 --> 00:38:22,501
Are you all right?

270
00:38:22,676 --> 00:38:25,388
Your aunt said for you not to get too excited!

271
00:38:25,471 --> 00:38:26,597
Should I get your medicine?

272
00:38:27,233 --> 00:38:29,027
No, that's okay, Miss Hara.

273
00:38:29,047 --> 00:38:30,841
I'm actually feeling pretty good.

274
00:38:37,775 --> 00:38:40,277
Nesting season?

275
00:38:48,077 --> 00:38:51,914
Well, Shawn, you have a nice, long rest now.

276
00:39:51,474 --> 00:39:52,641
Papa!

277
00:39:54,477 --> 00:39:57,313
I hear you visited the young bean.

278
00:39:57,396 --> 00:39:58,814
I'm sorry.

279
00:39:59,398 --> 00:40:01,650
I went to ask him to leave us alone.

280
00:40:02,234 --> 00:40:04,487
But I really don't think he intends to hurt us.

281
00:40:05,863 --> 00:40:08,699
Many Borrowers have lost their lives thinking the same.

282
00:40:10,117 --> 00:40:12,077
It must never happen again.

283
00:40:12,171 --> 00:40:13,152
- Do you understand me?

284
00:40:13,172 --> 00:40:14,153
- Yeah.

285
00:40:24,006 --> 00:40:26,091
We'd better start looking for a new home.

286
00:40:29,678 --> 00:40:31,514
The boy knows that we're here.

287
00:40:35,851 --> 00:40:36,936
Are we safe?

288
00:41:10,938 --> 00:41:11,898
Delivery.

289
00:41:11,918 --> 00:41:12,878
Package for you, ma'am.

290
00:41:15,693 --> 00:41:17,049
Thanks for the drink, Hara.

291
00:41:17,069 --> 00:41:18,425
It's pretty hot today.

292
00:41:18,769 --> 00:41:22,606
Do you happen to know of any good pest control companies?

293
00:41:22,690 --> 00:41:24,650
Pest problem?

294
00:41:26,735 --> 00:41:30,656
Here's one. "Squeaky Klean Pest Extermination."

295
00:41:30,749 --> 00:41:32,293
1-800...

296
00:41:32,313 --> 00:41:33,857
Oh, hang on.

297
00:41:37,538 --> 00:41:40,833
So you got yourself a mouse problem?

298
00:41:40,916 --> 00:41:44,420
Maybe it's mice, maybe it's little tiny people.

299
00:41:46,046 --> 00:41:51,343
Strange things have been happening here and I know why.

300
00:41:51,885 --> 00:41:54,346
That's just the craziest thing I've ever heard.

301
00:41:54,430 --> 00:41:57,683
I mean, when Hara told me, I just couldn't believe it.

302
00:41:57,766 --> 00:42:00,728
Why on earth would a crow try to fly into your room?

303
00:42:01,603 --> 00:42:03,564
Were you frightened?

304
00:42:03,657 --> 00:42:06,765
No, I wasn't scared.

305
00:42:06,785 --> 00:42:09,893
Hara came and chased it away And it's a good thing I came in when I did.

306
00:42:09,987 --> 00:42:12,865
That bird had huge wings and claws...

307
00:42:12,948 --> 00:42:20,456
Let's not relive the excitement, Hara, considering Shawn came here for a little peace and quiet and tranquility before his operation.

308
00:42:21,342 --> 00:42:22,510
Yes, ma'am.

309
00:42:22,530 --> 00:42:23,698
Forgive me.

310
00:42:26,555 --> 00:42:28,621
I'm sorry, Hara.

311
00:42:28,641 --> 00:42:30,707
I don't mean to be short with you.

312
00:42:30,799 --> 00:42:35,137
But why his mother chose this time to go away on business is just beyond...

313
00:42:35,763 --> 00:42:40,225
It must be terribly hard for you without your mother here to look after you.

314
00:42:40,309 --> 00:42:42,603
You know, not so much lately.

315
00:42:43,228 --> 00:42:48,233
I suppose the divorce couldn't be helped, but honestly, why couldn't she be here when her son needs her so?

316
00:42:48,317 --> 00:42:50,903
It's the last thing his poor heart needs.

317
00:42:59,119 --> 00:43:02,581
Aunt Jessica, I was noticing that miniature house in my room.

318
00:43:02,664 --> 00:43:04,166
And the detail's amazing.

319
00:43:04,249 --> 00:43:06,418
Oh, you mean the dollhouse.

320
00:43:06,502 --> 00:43:09,588
That beautiful little house belonged to your mother.

321
00:43:09,671 --> 00:43:13,258
She had to leave it here when she moved away to go to college.

322
00:43:13,342 --> 00:43:14,510
It was Mother's?

323
00:43:14,968 --> 00:43:21,517
Your grandfather had it specially made because he was hoping it would be a lovely home for the little people.

324
00:43:21,683 --> 00:43:22,893
What?

325
00:43:22,986 --> 00:43:24,656
That's right.

326
00:43:24,676 --> 00:43:26,346
Little people who lived in the walls.

327
00:43:26,438 --> 00:43:28,107
He was quite obsessed with them.

328
00:43:28,816 --> 00:43:31,193
People laughed, of course, and called him mad.

329
00:43:31,276 --> 00:43:33,612
But your mother, she believed him.

330
00:43:34,321 --> 00:43:37,533
They worked on that house together for hours.

331
00:43:37,616 --> 00:43:41,703
And he told her they would come, but of course, they never did.

332
00:43:42,204 --> 00:43:46,959
Tell me, Shawn, have you ever seen any tiny little people in your room?

333
00:43:49,670 --> 00:43:52,381
Can't say that I have.

334
00:43:53,549 --> 00:43:56,969
I think it's why your mother doesn't like to come here any more.

335
00:43:57,052 --> 00:44:00,889
Too many memories of wishes that never came true.

336
00:44:01,223 --> 00:44:02,766
Can we look inside it?

337
00:44:03,225 --> 00:44:04,226
Yes!

338
00:44:05,102 --> 00:44:09,231
You know, I haven't looked inside it in quite a long time.

339
00:44:13,318 --> 00:44:16,321
Hara, could you be a dear and turn off the lights?

340
00:44:16,405 --> 00:44:17,739
Ma'am.

341
00:44:24,580 --> 00:44:31,128
So many years have passed This is the living room.

342
00:44:31,211 --> 00:44:36,216
Your grandfather had all of this handmade by a real furniture maker in England.

343
00:44:36,842 --> 00:44:39,553
Isn't that just insane?

344
00:44:40,345 --> 00:44:42,806
Look at the attention to detail.

345
00:44:42,890 --> 00:44:45,267
They really were preparing it for someone to live in.

346
00:44:45,809 --> 00:44:53,317
And just in case you don't believe what I'm saying is absolutely true, have a look at that room right there.

347
00:44:58,238 --> 00:45:02,618
Come in the garden What a kitchen!

348
00:45:02,701 --> 00:45:06,705
And look at the trees Everything in it a miniature of the real thing.

349
00:45:06,798 --> 00:45:08,551
That oven actually works.

350
00:45:08,571 --> 00:45:10,324
You could bake real cookies.

351
00:45:10,751 --> 00:45:12,794
Some really little cookies.

352
00:45:12,878 --> 00:45:15,547
What a pity their dream never came true.

353
00:45:17,257 --> 00:45:20,385
It really would've made a lovely home.

354
00:45:21,929 --> 00:47:45,447
Settled down there long ago So many years have passed The dew is still on the roses I left my childhood In a garden green Come in the garden And sit on the grass I used to sit there when I was a child Ivy and moss Little daisies Covered the lane long ago You know, Mother, we've had these same pictures for years.

355
00:47:45,530 --> 00:47:46,740
Wouldn't you like some new ones?

356
00:47:47,074 --> 00:47:49,868
Well, Arrietty, I like those pictures.

357
00:47:49,951 --> 00:47:53,747
And I've always dreamed I'd see the real ocean someday.

358
00:47:54,873 --> 00:47:57,751
Besides, there's no point in changing them now.

359
00:48:02,464 --> 00:48:04,883
I wonder what's taking Papa so long.

360
00:48:04,966 --> 00:48:08,220
Why is my first thought always that he got eaten by the cat?

361
00:48:08,303 --> 00:48:09,471
What's wrong with me?

362
00:48:13,016 --> 00:48:14,059
There he is!

363
00:48:14,142 --> 00:48:15,811
Does he look eaten?

364
00:48:18,730 --> 00:48:20,357
Hey, Papa, how was it out there?

365
00:48:23,360 --> 00:48:25,487
I slipped and twisted my leg.

366
00:48:25,570 --> 00:48:27,614
I'm lucky that Spiller here found me.

367
00:48:33,704 --> 00:48:35,122
Well, what is going on down...

368
00:48:35,205 --> 00:48:37,249
Pod, you're hurt!

369
00:48:37,342 --> 00:48:38,532
It was the cat, wasn't it?

370
00:48:38,552 --> 00:48:39,742
See, I'm not crazy.

371
00:48:39,835 --> 00:48:41,002
Get up here!

372
00:48:42,170 --> 00:48:43,422
Does it hurt, Papa?

373
00:48:43,515 --> 00:48:45,017
It's just a sprain.

374
00:48:45,037 --> 00:48:46,539
Go calm your mother.

375
00:48:47,728 --> 00:48:48,646
I'll get some cold water.

376
00:48:48,666 --> 00:48:49,584
I'll be right back.

377
00:48:49,678 --> 00:48:51,304
Everyone relax!

378
00:48:52,524 --> 00:48:53,464
Here's a towel.

379
00:48:53,484 --> 00:48:54,424
Dry yourself.

380
00:48:54,516 --> 00:48:56,852
Who's that?

381
00:49:02,107 --> 00:49:05,193
I wonder if he has news about any of the other Borrowers.

382
00:49:13,702 --> 00:49:15,036
Okay, I leave now.

383
00:49:15,120 --> 00:49:18,206
Can't you at least stay and have some tea?

384
00:49:26,047 --> 00:49:27,966
Arrietty, I'll take care of your father.

385
00:49:28,049 --> 00:49:30,927
Why don't you see if Spiller would like a cup of tea?

386
00:49:32,230 --> 00:49:33,983
Won't you please stay, Spiller?

387
00:49:34,003 --> 00:49:35,756
I've never met another Borrower before.

388
00:49:39,561 --> 00:49:41,897
We can't thank you enough for your help.

389
00:49:42,606 --> 00:49:44,983
Tell us, have you seen other Borrowers?

390
00:49:45,076 --> 00:49:47,142
We're all alone here and we're starting to believe we're the only ones left.

391
00:49:47,162 --> 00:49:49,228
Are we?

392
00:49:52,991 --> 00:49:53,992
This many.

393
00:49:54,085 --> 00:49:55,734
Oh!

394
00:49:55,754 --> 00:49:57,403
Then cousin Lupy could still be alive.

395
00:49:59,216 --> 00:50:00,259
Oh, that's a bow, isn't it?

396
00:50:00,279 --> 00:50:01,322
Can I see it?

397
00:50:07,255 --> 00:50:09,591
You use this for your borrowing?

398
00:50:14,387 --> 00:50:17,933
Give that back, Arrietty, before you shoot someone's eye out.

399
00:50:32,374 --> 00:50:33,293
Okay.

400
00:50:33,313 --> 00:50:34,232
Go now.

401
00:50:35,116 --> 00:50:38,286
Oh, but couldn't you stay a little bit longer?

402
00:50:38,370 --> 00:50:39,913
I'll cook dinner.

403
00:50:42,165 --> 00:50:43,792
Already got this.

404
00:50:46,753 --> 00:50:48,922
A cricket leg!

405
00:50:50,298 --> 00:50:51,842
Want some?

406
00:50:51,935 --> 00:50:52,895
- Very fresh.

407
00:50:52,915 --> 00:50:53,875
- No, thanks.

408
00:50:58,849 --> 00:51:00,058
Bye.

409
00:51:01,226 --> 00:51:02,811
Thank you, my friend.

410
00:51:06,157 --> 00:51:07,159
I'll go with him.

411
00:51:07,179 --> 00:51:08,181
To see him out.

412
00:51:14,281 --> 00:51:17,242
What were you doing out there in that storm?

413
00:51:17,868 --> 00:51:20,287
I was looking for a safe route for our journey.

414
00:51:20,370 --> 00:51:22,372
And now I know which route not to take.

415
00:51:22,455 --> 00:51:23,832
Oh, Pod.

416
00:51:24,165 --> 00:51:27,669
Spiller knows of more Borrowers a few days journey away.

417
00:51:28,545 --> 00:51:30,755
There's a small river past the forest.

418
00:51:30,839 --> 00:51:32,507
He's offered to take us on it.

419
00:51:33,008 --> 00:51:34,843
That's great.

420
00:51:36,469 --> 00:51:39,514
I'm sure we'll find a new place in no time.

421
00:51:40,432 --> 00:51:44,144
And I'm sure it will almost be as nice as this.

422
00:51:48,398 --> 00:51:50,233
I'm really glad I met you, Spiller.

423
00:51:50,317 --> 00:51:51,651
Or that I met anyone.

424
00:51:52,193 --> 00:51:54,696
Hey, maybe next time you could bring your whole family with you.

425
00:51:55,373 --> 00:51:56,688
No family.

426
00:51:56,708 --> 00:51:58,023
Only Spiller.

427
00:52:00,045 --> 00:52:00,900
Well, we...

428
00:52:00,920 --> 00:52:01,775
We could be a family.

429
00:52:01,870 --> 00:52:04,414
And when you come back you could stay for a family dinner.

430
00:53:09,938 --> 00:53:11,231
Hara?

431
00:53:29,791 --> 00:53:32,919
Arrietty, your stitches need to be closer together.

432
00:53:33,003 --> 00:53:34,462
You'll have to start over.

433
00:53:36,631 --> 00:53:38,633
Why do we need such a big bag anyway?

434
00:53:38,717 --> 00:53:40,719
Are we putting the whole house in here?

435
00:53:48,184 --> 00:53:51,104
I think I'm gonna go check on Papa.

436
00:53:53,064 --> 00:53:55,608
Papa, can I come in?

437
00:53:57,871 --> 00:53:59,415
- How's your leg?

438
00:53:59,435 --> 00:54:00,979
- Well, better than that cricket's.

439
00:54:01,072 --> 00:54:02,407
I'm serious.

440
00:54:06,077 --> 00:54:07,787
Papa, why do we have to move?

441
00:54:08,913 --> 00:54:12,584
Once a Borrower has been seen, the beans' curiosity can't be stopped.

442
00:54:16,337 --> 00:54:20,008
Well, isn't it possible that not every human bean is dangerous?

443
00:54:21,384 --> 00:54:27,807
Arrietty, before you were born there were two other families who were living in this house.

444
00:54:28,224 --> 00:54:31,311
One family went missing, they just disappeared.

445
00:54:31,394 --> 00:54:33,605
The other one moved away.

446
00:54:33,688 --> 00:54:35,398
They were seen by humans.

447
00:54:35,482 --> 00:54:39,527
And so, we have to do whatever it takes to survive.

448
00:54:40,653 --> 00:54:41,946
But, Papa...

449
00:54:50,298 --> 00:54:50,883
Oh!

450
00:54:50,903 --> 00:54:51,488
Oh, no!

451
00:54:57,722 --> 00:54:59,558
Pod, what is it?

452
00:54:59,578 --> 00:55:01,414
An earthquake?

453
00:55:26,074 --> 00:55:27,325
Mother!

454
00:55:29,202 --> 00:55:31,955
It won't open!

455
00:55:34,415 --> 00:55:37,043
Frame is buckled!

456
00:55:59,399 --> 00:56:00,650
The wall!

457
00:56:36,895 --> 00:56:38,188
Homily!

458
00:56:39,939 --> 00:56:41,357
Homily, are you all right?

459
00:56:42,275 --> 00:56:46,654
Pod, remember how I always said I wanted a new kitchen?

460
00:57:07,550 --> 00:57:10,053
More bills.

461
00:57:52,095 --> 00:57:54,389
Remember, take only the things we need.

462
00:58:02,063 --> 00:58:04,232
We can't possibly carry all of this.

463
00:58:05,149 --> 00:58:08,903
And, Homily, don't take anything from the dollhouse.

464
00:58:10,613 --> 00:58:13,032
I'm gonna go make sure that it's safe.

465
00:58:13,751 --> 00:58:15,045
- You stay with your mother.

466
00:58:15,065 --> 00:58:16,359
- Okay.

467
00:58:48,484 --> 00:58:50,069
So you finally came.

468
00:59:00,204 --> 00:59:02,832
Did you like your new kitchen?

469
00:59:04,792 --> 00:59:07,003
Well, our house looks like a train wreck.

470
00:59:09,140 --> 00:59:10,663
But it doesn't matter.

471
00:59:10,683 --> 00:59:12,206
Because I came to tell you goodbye.

472
00:59:17,305 --> 00:59:18,973
Can I turn around?

473
00:59:43,122 --> 00:59:44,749
You're beautiful.

474
00:59:47,835 --> 00:59:49,754
My papa said we have to move now.

475
00:59:52,215 --> 00:59:56,386
We've been seen, and Borrowers aren't supposed to be seen.

476
00:59:56,928 --> 00:59:58,429
What are Borrowers?

477
00:59:58,513 --> 01:00:00,932
My mother, father, and I are all Borrowers.

478
01:00:01,015 --> 01:00:03,393
We borrow things that beans won't miss if they are gone.

479
01:00:04,018 --> 01:00:06,938
Just little things, soap, cookies, and sugar.

480
01:00:07,021 --> 01:00:09,107
All things that we need to survive.

481
01:00:09,190 --> 01:00:11,275
Even my great-grandfather was a Borrower.

482
01:00:12,527 --> 01:00:14,779
I think my grandfather saw one of you once.

483
01:00:14,862 --> 01:00:16,906
It's possible.

484
01:00:19,992 --> 01:00:21,869
And it's my fault that you're leaving.

485
01:00:22,213 --> 01:00:23,278
Niya!

486
01:00:23,298 --> 01:00:24,363
Niya!

487
01:00:24,465 --> 01:00:25,800
Don't be like that.

488
01:00:25,820 --> 01:00:27,155
Be nice to her.

489
01:00:28,167 --> 01:00:32,338
So, in my aunt's house, how many other Borrowers are there who are living with you?

490
01:00:33,256 --> 01:00:36,634
It's just my father and my mother and me.

491
01:00:37,051 --> 01:00:38,719
What about in other houses?

492
01:00:38,803 --> 01:00:40,221
I'm sure there are some.

493
01:00:40,304 --> 01:00:42,974
But I've only met one other so far.

494
01:00:46,018 --> 01:00:49,313
You must be afraid you'll be the only ones of your kind who are left.

495
01:00:49,397 --> 01:00:50,731
What?

496
01:00:50,815 --> 01:00:53,401
Every year there's fewer and fewer of you, right?

497
01:00:53,985 --> 01:00:57,280
Aren't you scared that soon you'll all be gone?

498
01:00:59,240 --> 01:01:01,117
What a horrible thing to say!

499
01:01:01,200 --> 01:01:04,662
I know that there's more of us because Spiller said so!

500
01:01:05,288 --> 01:01:06,664
Who's Spiller?

501
01:01:06,757 --> 01:01:09,803
He's one of us.

502
01:01:09,823 --> 01:01:12,869
He lives out in the forest, and he said that there are hundreds more of us.

503
01:01:13,546 --> 01:01:14,964
That might be true.

504
01:01:15,047 --> 01:01:17,842
But, you know, none of us can live forever, can we?

505
01:01:20,094 --> 01:01:22,430
We all have to die sometime.

506
01:01:23,097 --> 01:01:25,057
Why would you say something like that?

507
01:01:25,975 --> 01:01:27,602
Because it's true.

508
01:01:28,019 --> 01:01:29,729
I guess so.

509
01:01:30,188 --> 01:01:32,773
Believe me, I know what I'm talking about.

510
01:01:33,232 --> 01:01:37,278
Sometimes things happen to us that are just beyond our control.

511
01:01:39,113 --> 01:01:43,075
And when these things happen, there's really nothing you can do about it.

512
01:01:43,784 --> 01:01:46,496
You just accept it and prepare for the worst.

513
01:01:48,039 --> 01:01:49,749
I wish it wasn't that way.

514
01:01:49,832 --> 01:01:53,127
But you can't live a life that's built on nothing but wishes.

515
01:01:54,295 --> 01:01:56,297
It isn't practical.

516
01:01:56,380 --> 01:01:59,300
Sometimes you just have to accept the hand of fate.

517
01:01:59,842 --> 01:02:01,969
Oh, no, you don't.

518
01:02:02,803 --> 01:02:07,475
Sometimes you have to stand up and fight for the things that are worth fighting for.

519
01:02:08,611 --> 01:02:10,071
You have to survive.

520
01:02:10,091 --> 01:02:11,551
That's what my papa says.

521
01:02:11,646 --> 01:02:14,649
And so we're leaving even though it's dangerous.

522
01:02:15,274 --> 01:02:17,568
And we are going to survive.

523
01:02:17,662 --> 01:02:19,331
We are Borrowers and we'll make do.

524
01:02:19,351 --> 01:02:21,020
We always have.

525
01:02:21,113 --> 01:02:24,492
As long as we have each other to live for, we'll keep on living.

526
01:02:27,004 --> 01:02:28,569
I'm sorry.

527
01:02:28,589 --> 01:02:30,154
I didn't mean to upset you.

528
01:02:31,332 --> 01:02:33,626
I'm actually the one who's going to die.

529
01:02:34,126 --> 01:02:35,503
What?

530
01:02:38,589 --> 01:02:40,550
There's something wrong with my heart.

531
01:02:40,633 --> 01:02:44,762
They're gonna operate next week but it probably won't help.

532
01:02:44,845 --> 01:02:46,264
That's terrible.

533
01:02:48,641 --> 01:02:51,811
I've always been sick and I've had someone looking after me.

534
01:02:52,812 --> 01:02:57,525
And that's why when I saw you, I just wanted to find a way to protect you.

535
01:02:57,608 --> 01:03:00,236
But I guess I messed up.

536
01:03:00,329 --> 01:03:01,456
I made it worse.

537
01:03:01,476 --> 01:03:02,603
I'm sorry.

538
01:03:04,532 --> 01:03:07,159
And I'm sorry to hear about your heart.

539
01:03:31,267 --> 01:03:33,936
Now what on earth is this doing here?

540
01:04:00,046 --> 01:04:03,924
Now how did you get in there?

541
01:04:20,441 --> 01:04:22,526
There you are!

542
01:04:24,570 --> 01:04:26,030
Mom!

543
01:04:27,458 --> 01:04:28,543
What?

544
01:04:28,563 --> 01:04:29,648
What's wrong?

545
01:04:29,742 --> 01:04:32,828
My mother, I think she's in danger.

546
01:04:44,131 --> 01:04:45,424
No!

547
01:04:53,140 --> 01:04:54,975
Give me that, you little thief!

548
01:05:04,193 --> 01:05:07,154
Now we'll see who they call crazy.

549
01:05:07,988 --> 01:05:11,826
And I bet there's more of you, aren't there?

550
01:05:13,587 --> 01:05:14,387
Wait, no!

551
01:05:14,407 --> 01:05:15,207
Wait, wait!

552
01:05:15,227 --> 01:05:16,027
Wait!

553
01:05:33,514 --> 01:05:34,640
I have to go help her.

554
01:05:35,891 --> 01:05:37,184
But...

555
01:06:00,718 --> 01:06:01,532
Oh, no!

556
01:06:01,552 --> 01:06:02,366
Help!

557
01:06:02,386 --> 01:06:03,200
No, no, please!

558
01:06:03,220 --> 01:06:04,034
Help!

559
01:06:04,138 --> 01:06:05,098
Pod!

560
01:06:05,118 --> 01:06:06,078
Arrietty!

561
01:06:10,092 --> 01:06:11,385
Let me out of here!

562
01:06:20,321 --> 01:06:21,176
Hey!

563
01:06:21,196 --> 01:06:22,051
Hey!

564
01:06:24,033 --> 01:06:24,639
Hey!

565
01:06:24,659 --> 01:06:25,265
Hey!

566
01:06:25,285 --> 01:06:25,891
Let me out of here!

567
01:06:26,202 --> 01:06:27,329
Arrietty!

568
01:06:27,349 --> 01:06:28,476
Help!

569
01:06:32,239 --> 01:06:33,866
Watch it!

570
01:06:48,923 --> 01:06:50,591
Let's see.

571
01:06:56,680 --> 01:06:58,933
Now to find the others.

572
01:06:59,527 --> 01:07:00,272
Let me out!

573
01:07:00,292 --> 01:07:01,037
No!

574
01:07:01,057 --> 01:07:01,802
No!

575
01:07:34,009 --> 01:07:35,970
Something terrible has happened.

576
01:09:01,273 --> 01:09:02,421
- Squeaky Klean.

577
01:09:02,441 --> 01:09:03,589
- Yes, hello.

578
01:09:03,682 --> 01:09:06,101
I'm calling from 833 Elm Lane.

579
01:09:06,185 --> 01:09:08,103
Could you get out here right away?

580
01:09:08,395 --> 01:09:11,440
I have a very unique pest problem.

581
01:09:11,533 --> 01:09:13,057
- Is it mice?

582
01:09:13,077 --> 01:09:14,601
- Oh, much worse than mice.

583
01:09:15,235 --> 01:09:17,154
Do you want them exterminated?

584
01:09:17,237 --> 01:09:19,949
No, I need you to trap them.

585
01:09:31,095 --> 01:09:31,687
Shawn!

586
01:09:31,707 --> 01:09:32,299
Shawn!

587
01:09:32,319 --> 01:09:32,911
Shawn!

588
01:09:33,597 --> 01:09:34,954
Shawn!

589
01:09:34,974 --> 01:09:36,331
Shawn!

590
01:09:36,423 --> 01:09:37,675
Arrietty!

591
01:09:43,472 --> 01:09:45,015
My mother is missing.

592
01:09:45,484 --> 01:09:47,279
Someone took the roof off!

593
01:09:47,299 --> 01:09:49,094
I think a human bean got her.

594
01:09:55,275 --> 01:09:56,527
Oh, Mama.

595
01:10:07,371 --> 01:10:08,914
We will find her.

596
01:10:41,613 --> 01:10:42,823
What?

597
01:10:44,241 --> 01:10:45,868
Someone's locked us in.

598
01:10:50,257 --> 01:10:51,300
There's a room next door.

599
01:10:51,320 --> 01:10:52,363
Hold on tight.

600
01:10:59,131 --> 01:11:00,758
One step at a time.

601
01:11:00,841 --> 01:11:01,967
Right.

602
01:11:11,602 --> 01:11:12,728
It's stuck!

603
01:11:13,020 --> 01:11:14,271
Wait.

604
01:11:24,490 --> 01:11:25,616
I can get us in.

605
01:11:49,807 --> 01:11:51,391
Oh, no, no!

606
01:12:01,110 --> 01:12:02,194
Keep going.

607
01:12:37,813 --> 01:12:40,065
What do you mean you're lost?

608
01:12:40,649 --> 01:12:43,026
How can you possibly be lost?

609
01:12:43,110 --> 01:12:44,653
It's the only road!

610
01:12:44,746 --> 01:12:45,908
- Is it before the bridge?

611
01:12:45,928 --> 01:12:47,090
- What bridge?

612
01:12:47,110 --> 01:12:48,272
There's no bridge!

613
01:12:55,998 --> 01:12:57,791
Hara must have found it and opened it.

614
01:12:57,875 --> 01:12:59,459
This is what I was afraid of.

615
01:12:59,543 --> 01:13:01,128
Mother's been taken.

616
01:13:37,956 --> 01:13:39,541
Are you okay?

617
01:13:40,135 --> 01:13:41,200
Be careful.

618
01:13:41,220 --> 01:13:42,285
Shawn, please.

619
01:13:49,551 --> 01:13:52,179
Where are those idiots?

620
01:14:26,348 --> 01:14:27,683
Mother!

621
01:14:27,703 --> 01:14:29,038
Where are you?

622
01:14:29,935 --> 01:14:31,584
Be wise.

623
01:14:31,604 --> 01:14:33,253
They're supposed to catch pests.

624
01:14:45,075 --> 01:14:46,181
But...

625
01:14:46,201 --> 01:14:47,307
HOW did you...

626
01:14:47,401 --> 01:14:48,694
Hara.

627
01:14:51,113 --> 01:14:53,282
Could I have some warm milk?

628
01:14:53,375 --> 01:14:54,543
Okay!

629
01:14:54,563 --> 01:14:55,731
Wait just a minute.

630
01:15:05,752 --> 01:15:07,296
Thank you, Hara.

631
01:15:45,344 --> 01:15:46,659
I'm a little hungry.

632
01:15:46,679 --> 01:15:47,994
Are there any cookies?

633
01:15:48,096 --> 01:15:49,536
Cookies?

634
01:15:49,556 --> 01:15:50,996
Now he wants cookies.

635
01:15:54,551 --> 01:15:56,094
Mother!

636
01:15:57,679 --> 01:15:59,097
Mother!

637
01:16:06,646 --> 01:16:08,065
Mother!

638
01:16:08,148 --> 01:16:09,399
Arrietty!

639
01:16:13,236 --> 01:16:14,654
Over here!

640
01:16:16,500 --> 01:16:17,217
Arrietty!

641
01:16:17,237 --> 01:16:17,954
Here I am!

642
01:16:17,974 --> 01:16:18,691
Here I am!

643
01:16:19,117 --> 01:16:20,535
Oh, Mother!

644
01:16:23,663 --> 01:16:25,374
Oh, Arrietty.

645
01:16:52,661 --> 01:16:53,704
Oh, good.

646
01:16:53,724 --> 01:16:54,767
There they are.

647
01:16:54,871 --> 01:16:56,269
They finally found the road.

648
01:16:56,289 --> 01:16:57,687
The only road.

649
01:17:18,510 --> 01:17:20,595
Another bean!

650
01:17:24,609 --> 01:17:25,381
It's okay, Mother.

651
01:17:25,401 --> 01:17:26,173
He's a friend.

652
01:17:47,914 --> 01:17:51,418
Ma'am, we'd like to take a look around.

653
01:17:51,501 --> 01:17:52,669
See what we see.

654
01:17:52,752 --> 01:17:54,254
Yes, of course.

655
01:18:18,445 --> 01:18:21,448
Squeaky Klean Exterminators?

656
01:18:21,791 --> 01:18:22,772
Hara?

657
01:18:22,792 --> 01:18:23,773
Hara!

658
01:18:24,618 --> 01:18:25,660
Oh!

659
01:18:26,912 --> 01:18:28,663
What's going on here?

660
01:18:28,747 --> 01:18:30,665
It's finally happened.

661
01:18:30,749 --> 01:18:32,709
I found the little people.

662
01:18:32,792 --> 01:18:34,211
Little people?

663
01:18:35,347 --> 01:18:37,037
Yes!

664
01:18:37,057 --> 01:18:38,747
And what little robbers they are.

665
01:18:51,071 --> 01:18:53,470
I wouldn't have believed it either unless I'd seen it with my own eyes.

666
01:18:53,490 --> 01:18:55,889
It's remarkable!

667
01:18:55,982 --> 01:18:58,777
It's the eighth wonder of the world.

668
01:18:59,486 --> 01:19:02,113
And they're so teeny!

669
01:19:02,197 --> 01:19:05,492
And they have a whole house full of things they've stolen.

670
01:19:05,951 --> 01:19:08,036
Are you sure you didn't find the sherry again?

671
01:19:08,411 --> 01:19:11,581
All these years you thought I was losing things.

672
01:19:11,675 --> 01:19:12,906
But it wasn't me.

673
01:19:12,926 --> 01:19:14,157
It was them!

674
01:19:14,251 --> 01:19:17,462
You didn't mention little people to the exterminators, did you?

675
01:19:17,556 --> 01:19:18,578
No.

676
01:19:18,598 --> 01:19:19,620
I didn't want to scare them off.

677
01:19:19,714 --> 01:19:22,175
Because I'm sure the house is just full of them.

678
01:19:23,969 --> 01:19:26,263
You'll see when I show you.

679
01:19:26,638 --> 01:19:29,015
This is their nest.

680
01:19:30,892 --> 01:19:33,520
Nest?

681
01:19:38,066 --> 01:19:40,902
Looks like a pile of old junk to me.

682
01:19:40,986 --> 01:19:42,862
What?

683
01:19:43,582 --> 01:19:44,709
It was here!

684
01:19:44,729 --> 01:19:45,856
It was here!

685
01:19:47,534 --> 01:19:48,952
Where's that little teapot?

686
01:19:49,035 --> 01:19:51,955
Okay, Hara, I'm sending the exterminators away.

687
01:19:52,048 --> 01:19:52,779
No!

688
01:19:52,799 --> 01:19:53,530
No, no!

689
01:19:53,550 --> 01:19:54,281
Wait just a minute.

690
01:19:55,051 --> 01:19:55,921
Oh.

691
01:19:55,941 --> 01:19:56,811
Oh!

692
01:19:56,831 --> 01:19:57,701
I'll clean that up later.

693
01:19:59,921 --> 01:20:02,173
Oh, please!

694
01:20:05,520 --> 01:20:07,044
Hello, Shawn.

695
01:20:07,064 --> 01:20:08,588
Can we come in for a minute?

696
01:20:08,680 --> 01:20:09,723
It's open.

697
01:20:20,619 --> 01:20:22,538
You'll see.

698
01:20:22,558 --> 01:20:24,477
Those little thieves stole the tiny kitchen.

699
01:20:26,531 --> 01:20:29,868
I don't know how they did it, but the whole thing is gone.

700
01:20:32,746 --> 01:20:33,913
Not gone.

701
01:20:33,997 --> 01:20:36,333
Perhaps you need a little time off, Hara.

702
01:20:37,959 --> 01:20:40,503
Yeah.

703
01:20:48,730 --> 01:20:49,669
Wait!

704
01:20:49,689 --> 01:20:50,628
Wait!

705
01:20:50,648 --> 01:20:51,587
I can prove it!

706
01:20:51,681 --> 01:20:53,808
I've got one of them in a jar!

707
01:20:56,404 --> 01:20:58,324
Poor Hara.

708
01:20:58,344 --> 01:21:00,264
I think she's finally gone bonkers.

709
01:21:02,275 --> 01:21:05,862
Do I smell fresh herbs?

710
01:21:18,917 --> 01:21:22,504
Someone's been making tea.

711
01:21:24,464 --> 01:21:26,466
It's just as my father told us.

712
01:21:26,549 --> 01:21:28,843
There really are little people living here.

713
01:21:32,138 --> 01:21:33,348
Yes, there are.

714
01:21:34,140 --> 01:21:36,559
Your mother really should be here to see this.

715
01:21:36,643 --> 01:21:39,562
She waited so long for some proof of them.

716
01:21:39,646 --> 01:21:41,731
But they're not thieves like Hara said.

717
01:21:41,815 --> 01:21:43,066
They're just Borrowers.

718
01:21:43,149 --> 01:21:44,401
What?

719
01:21:45,026 --> 01:21:47,737
I mean, they must be very frightened.

720
01:21:49,989 --> 01:21:52,367
I just hope they're still here.

721
01:21:57,372 --> 01:21:58,707
I hope so, too.

722
01:22:13,481 --> 01:22:14,400
Excuse me.

723
01:22:14,420 --> 01:22:15,339
Ma'am!

724
01:22:15,890 --> 01:22:18,059
Where would you like us to start looking?

725
01:22:26,609 --> 01:22:28,486
Oh, are you all right?

726
01:22:31,072 --> 01:22:33,074
Where did she go?

727
01:22:33,616 --> 01:22:36,035
Who took my lady?

728
01:22:36,337 --> 01:22:37,589
There are little people!

729
01:22:37,609 --> 01:22:38,861
There are!

730
01:22:38,955 --> 01:22:43,293
Easy, 68$)' And, no, I'm not losing my mind!

731
01:22:58,475 --> 01:23:01,186
If I collapse, leave me behind.

732
01:23:01,811 --> 01:23:02,937
With my tea kettle.

733
01:23:03,364 --> 01:23:05,284
You're doing great.

734
01:23:05,304 --> 01:23:07,224
It's just a little further until we break for food.

735
01:23:08,318 --> 01:23:09,986
Can't we just head back?

736
01:23:10,069 --> 01:23:13,156
We can live with the rats in the compost heap.

737
01:23:14,741 --> 01:23:16,159
Oh, no!

738
01:23:28,588 --> 01:23:29,923
Let's hurry.

739
01:23:31,382 --> 01:23:32,675
I can't do it.

740
01:23:59,077 --> 01:24:01,246
Arrietty, you really should eat something.

741
01:24:01,329 --> 01:24:03,873
We're gonna be walking at least until morning.

742
01:24:03,957 --> 01:24:05,124
What?

743
01:24:07,168 --> 01:24:08,753
I'm so sorry.

744
01:24:09,838 --> 01:24:14,926
I feel like maybe it's all my fault that we had to leave such a wonderful house.

745
01:24:18,513 --> 01:24:20,139
That's in the past.

746
01:24:21,432 --> 01:24:25,395
We'll make another wonderful house, the three of us, together.

747
01:24:31,359 --> 01:24:33,194
I'm going outside for a bit.

748
01:24:33,987 --> 01:24:36,322
Arrietty, don't go too far.

749
01:25:12,066 --> 01:25:13,359
Niya.

750
01:26:23,721 --> 01:26:25,014
Niya.

751
01:26:43,783 --> 01:26:45,326
Just a little further.

752
01:27:07,640 --> 01:27:09,600
Spiller!

753
01:27:24,407 --> 01:27:26,034
That's the last of it.

754
01:27:27,660 --> 01:27:29,495
Come on, we should keep moving.

755
01:27:29,829 --> 01:27:31,247
Okay.

756
01:27:35,668 --> 01:27:37,670
Mother, are you all right?

757
01:27:49,891 --> 01:27:51,267
Arrietty!

758
01:27:51,601 --> 01:27:52,894
Arrietty!

759
01:28:21,798 --> 01:28:22,965
Shawn.

760
01:28:26,928 --> 01:28:28,221
Arrietty.

761
01:28:45,238 --> 01:28:46,948
We have to leave.

762
01:28:47,031 --> 01:28:49,450
But Spiller says there's more of us not too far from here.

763
01:28:49,534 --> 01:28:51,410
A two-day's journey, at most.

764
01:28:52,411 --> 01:28:53,955
He thinks it might be my mother's family.

765
01:28:54,580 --> 01:28:56,457
You won't be the last of your kind.

766
01:28:56,541 --> 01:28:58,042
But how did you find me?

767
01:29:00,711 --> 01:29:02,588
Niya here showed me the way.

768
01:29:10,189 --> 01:29:11,587
Thank you, Niya.

769
01:29:11,607 --> 01:29:13,005
Take care of him.

770
01:29:19,397 --> 01:29:20,773
I brought you something.

771
01:29:26,571 --> 01:29:30,324
Now think of it as a gift from one friend to another.

772
01:29:35,788 --> 01:29:37,290
Thank you, Shawn.

773
01:29:51,262 --> 01:29:53,139
I have to go.

774
01:29:54,891 --> 01:29:56,642
When is your operation?

775
01:29:57,486 --> 01:29:58,926
Tomorrow.

776
01:29:58,946 --> 01:30:00,386
But I'm not scared.

777
01:30:00,479 --> 01:30:03,065
Because someone taught me how to be brave.

778
01:30:11,949 --> 01:30:13,618
So you'll remember me.

779
01:30:18,915 --> 01:30:20,625
How can I forget you?

780
01:30:27,006 --> 01:30:29,634
You protected me after all.

781
01:30:31,594 --> 01:30:33,429
Arrietty.

782
01:30:35,973 --> 01:30:38,851
I hope you have a happy life.

783
01:30:40,853 --> 01:30:42,396
Goodbye, Shawn.

784
01:30:46,567 --> 01:30:50,780
Arrietty, my heart is strong now because you're in it.

785
01:30:51,364 --> 01:30:53,407
And you always will be.

786
01:30:53,491 --> 01:30:54,784
Forever.

787
01:31:02,875 --> 01:31:04,543
I never saw her again.

